10
00:00:28,667 --> 00:00:34,330
So up until now, we've primarily worked in the area of interactive fiction.

11
00:00:34,330 --> 00:00:40,153
Inkle's over five years old now, and right from the start,

12
00:00:40,153 --> 00:00:43,194
our focus has been to take interactive fiction,

13
00:00:43,194 --> 00:00:46,536
which we believe to be this really rich medium,

14
00:00:46,536 --> 00:00:51,438
and make it a bit more just accessible for both gamers and non-gamers alike,

15
00:00:51,438 --> 00:00:52,359
because interactive fiction is...

16
00:00:53,619 --> 00:00:56,400
a beautiful medium and can do some amazing things,

17
00:00:56,400 --> 00:00:58,781
but not everyone has the inclination

18
00:00:58,781 --> 00:01:02,902
to use a Pazer-based game.

19
00:01:02,902 --> 00:01:04,643
It's quite hard to get into.

20
00:01:04,643 --> 00:01:06,904
So this is a clip from 80 Days,

21
00:01:06,904 --> 00:01:12,206
which is perhaps our most well-known game to date

22
00:01:12,206 --> 00:01:14,106
along with the Sorcery series.

23
00:01:14,106 --> 00:01:18,088
And as you can see, it has this prose-based flow

24
00:01:18,088 --> 00:01:18,768
at its heart.

25
00:01:20,068 --> 00:01:21,669
You could call it the core game loop.

26
00:01:21,669 --> 00:01:23,969
It's, in Halo terminology, you could call it

27
00:01:23,969 --> 00:01:25,810
the kind of the 30 seconds of fun.

28
00:01:25,810 --> 00:01:29,890
And there is the wider game, of course.

29
00:01:29,890 --> 00:01:31,891
There's a whole kind of board game-like layer

30
00:01:31,891 --> 00:01:34,691
where you can explore any way you want to go.

31
00:01:34,691 --> 00:01:37,552
There's almost 200 cities in the game,

32
00:01:37,552 --> 00:01:39,392
and you can go around the world any way you like.

33
00:01:39,392 --> 00:01:41,113
So there is the strategic layer.

34
00:01:41,113 --> 00:01:45,053
But at its core, at its heart, is the narrative.

35
00:01:47,917 --> 00:01:52,260
And so clearly narrative is really important to us.

36
00:01:52,260 --> 00:01:55,362
In fact, it's so important that we built our own scripting

37
00:01:55,362 --> 00:01:58,685
language for it, our own narrative scripting language,

38
00:01:58,685 --> 00:02:00,606
which we call Ink.

39
00:02:00,606 --> 00:02:03,308
And all of our games so far, including 80 Days,

40
00:02:03,308 --> 00:02:04,509
were written in Ink.

41
00:02:04,509 --> 00:02:07,811
And in fact, Ink is a language that we open sourced

42
00:02:07,811 --> 00:02:09,312
last year at GDC.

43
00:02:09,312 --> 00:02:14,917
And it's gone on to be used in a few projects that we're

44
00:02:14,917 --> 00:02:16,458
really excited to see, actually.

45
00:02:18,700 --> 00:02:25,246
So this is what seeing a city in 80 days looks like in ink.

46
00:02:25,246 --> 00:02:26,687
You don't need to obviously read all the text,

47
00:02:26,687 --> 00:02:29,870
but if you just pay attention to the rough ratio

48
00:02:29,870 --> 00:02:33,133
between just the prose, the core text,

49
00:02:33,133 --> 00:02:35,234
and all the little colored bits,

50
00:02:35,234 --> 00:02:37,136
so the blue and the green,

51
00:02:37,136 --> 00:02:39,859
they're the syntax and the logic which drive it.

52
00:02:40,654 --> 00:02:42,955
And if you look at the ratio between those two things,

53
00:02:42,955 --> 00:02:47,316
it really is focusing on the core text flow.

54
00:02:47,316 --> 00:02:50,456
It's allowing writers to just focus on the writing

55
00:02:50,456 --> 00:02:52,717
with just this lightweight markup

56
00:02:52,717 --> 00:02:55,858
to add the layer of interactivity.

57
00:02:55,858 --> 00:02:57,578
So we sort of like to think of it as

58
00:02:57,578 --> 00:03:00,559
markdown for interactive text.

59
00:03:02,150 --> 00:03:06,213
But now we're making a game that looks more like this,

60
00:03:06,213 --> 00:03:08,454
which I'm really super excited to show you

61
00:03:08,454 --> 00:03:10,455
because this is actually the first time

62
00:03:10,455 --> 00:03:12,237
that we've talked about it publicly.

63
00:03:12,237 --> 00:03:13,658
This is Heaven's Vault.

64
00:03:14,623 --> 00:03:20,148
It's a science fiction adventure featuring an archaeologist called

65
00:03:20,148 --> 00:03:24,611
Aaliyah Elazra, or El to her friends. It's set in a beautiful nebula

66
00:03:24,611 --> 00:03:31,917
scattered with the ancient ruins of a lost civilization. The player can fly anywhere between different moons,

67
00:03:31,917 --> 00:03:33,339
explore

68
00:03:33,339 --> 00:03:34,940
ruined cities,

69
00:03:34,940 --> 00:03:36,621
explore dig sites,

70
00:03:36,621 --> 00:03:38,203
uncover

71
00:03:38,203 --> 00:03:42,466
lost artifacts, with the story constantly unfolding around them as they go.

72
00:03:43,307 --> 00:03:46,569
And they can go between not just these kind of desolate locations,

73
00:03:46,569 --> 00:03:54,033
but also bustling markets and places with loads of different interesting characters to talk to.

74
00:03:54,033 --> 00:03:56,175
And so as you can see, it's a lot more graphical.

75
00:03:56,175 --> 00:03:59,977
This is actually a real screenshot from the game with just the text overlaid.

76
00:04:01,458 --> 00:04:05,361
So we have 3D worlds, we have 2D characters,

77
00:04:05,361 --> 00:04:08,343
and the structure superficially,

78
00:04:08,343 --> 00:04:09,844
it kind of resembles a point and click

79
00:04:09,844 --> 00:04:12,206
in that you can explore a space,

80
00:04:12,206 --> 00:04:14,728
you can interact with props and objects,

81
00:04:14,728 --> 00:04:15,909
and you can talk to characters.

82
00:04:15,909 --> 00:04:20,332
And the text is presented

83
00:04:20,332 --> 00:04:22,353
as kind of lightweight dialogue bubbles,

84
00:04:22,353 --> 00:04:25,135
and occasionally we also have narrated audio sections.

85
00:04:26,511 --> 00:04:30,873
But fundamentally, we're authoring this in exactly the same way as at 80 Days.

86
00:04:30,873 --> 00:04:35,235
So we still have this, basically a text adventure going on underneath the game

87
00:04:35,235 --> 00:04:37,856
that's kind of behind the scenes driving what happens in the game.

88
00:04:37,856 --> 00:04:38,436
So back to the talk's title.

89
00:04:38,436 --> 00:04:39,937
What do I mean by an interactive film script?

90
00:04:47,436 --> 00:04:51,918
So whereas 80 Days had that prose-based flow

91
00:04:51,918 --> 00:04:53,578
that it was like writing a novel

92
00:04:53,578 --> 00:04:56,199
with a bit of interactive markup.

93
00:04:56,199 --> 00:04:58,780
Similarly, Heaven's Vault is more like

94
00:04:58,780 --> 00:05:00,581
an interactive film script.

95
00:05:00,581 --> 00:05:03,823
So it has a film script, but with interactive markup,

96
00:05:03,823 --> 00:05:05,923
which changes the direction of the way

97
00:05:05,923 --> 00:05:07,404
that the script flows.

98
00:05:08,456 --> 00:05:11,718
and as it plays behind the scene it sort of generates

99
00:05:11,718 --> 00:05:13,459
as you make choices through the game.

100
00:05:13,459 --> 00:05:15,560
It generates more of a linear film script

101
00:05:15,560 --> 00:05:17,802
which drives the action in the game.

102
00:05:17,802 --> 00:05:21,124
And that sort of becomes like our blueprint

103
00:05:21,124 --> 00:05:23,525
or the blueprint for what happens in the game.

104
00:05:23,525 --> 00:05:26,507
So if we look at an example of a real film script,

105
00:05:26,507 --> 00:05:29,749
so this is page 24 from the screenplay of 2001 A Space Odyssey

106
00:05:33,514 --> 00:05:37,175
As well as the lines of dialogue, which are in the format you can see at the top,

107
00:05:37,175 --> 00:05:40,776
there are also instructions about how the scene is structured,

108
00:05:40,776 --> 00:05:45,398
and even editing decisions like that dissolve 2,

109
00:05:45,398 --> 00:05:50,319
which says exactly how the scene should be cut together in the final edit.

110
00:05:51,998 --> 00:05:55,902
And in the same way, the Heaven's Vault script

111
00:05:55,902 --> 00:05:58,906
has a mixture of dialogue, it has a bit of narration,

112
00:05:58,906 --> 00:06:00,688
and it also has those instructions,

113
00:06:00,688 --> 00:06:04,173
and those can be both interactive,

114
00:06:04,173 --> 00:06:06,536
so the choices that you make through the scene,

115
00:06:06,536 --> 00:06:08,398
but also just things like that,

116
00:06:08,398 --> 00:06:10,781
just the information about some of the transitions.

117
00:06:11,943 --> 00:06:16,426
Now I should say we're well aware of the dangers of getting too obsessed with the film industry

118
00:06:16,426 --> 00:06:20,850
and I know that a lot of game developers can be quite susceptible to it.

119
00:06:20,850 --> 00:06:26,014
So I would just like to say it is just a cute metaphor but it's quite a useful one nonetheless.

120
00:06:29,516 --> 00:06:31,237
So first of all, what I want to do

121
00:06:31,237 --> 00:06:35,838
is demonstrate exactly what a script editing workflow

122
00:06:35,838 --> 00:06:39,319
actually looks like using our ink editing tool, which

123
00:06:39,319 --> 00:06:44,221
is called Inky, which is also the name of my neighbor's cat.

124
00:06:44,601 --> 00:06:46,061
It's just a bit of fun.

125
00:06:46,061 --> 00:06:49,242
Ink is a custom Ink script writing tool

126
00:06:49,242 --> 00:06:51,902
that we built in the past year that's also open source,

127
00:06:51,902 --> 00:06:55,803
along with the Ink language.

128
00:06:55,803 --> 00:06:58,164
But with the main benefit that you can play as you write.

129
00:06:58,164 --> 00:06:59,444
So I'll show you in a moment.

130
00:06:59,444 --> 00:07:02,904
There are two panes, basically, one with the written text

131
00:07:02,904 --> 00:07:06,025
and one with the text flow that you're playing through

132
00:07:06,025 --> 00:07:06,625
and making choices.

133
00:07:06,625 --> 00:07:07,025
And I should also.

134
00:07:11,187 --> 00:07:13,748
warn you that you might have heard of programmer art.

135
00:07:13,748 --> 00:07:15,488
Well, this is going to be programmer writing.

136
00:07:15,488 --> 00:07:16,729
So I do apologize for that.

137
00:07:16,729 --> 00:07:19,130
So here we go.

138
00:07:19,130 --> 00:07:21,971
This is just a quick example using the character

139
00:07:21,971 --> 00:07:25,232
names from Heaven's Vault. So there's L and 6,

140
00:07:25,232 --> 00:07:27,313
her robot sidekick.

141
00:07:27,313 --> 00:07:30,374
And so far, this example has just got dialogue.

142
00:07:30,374 --> 00:07:31,354
It's got dialogue.

143
00:07:31,354 --> 00:07:32,435
It's got a few choices.

144
00:07:37,490 --> 00:07:39,752
We can see an example of making a choice,

145
00:07:39,752 --> 00:07:42,475
and you can see what happens as it drills

146
00:07:42,475 --> 00:07:46,398
into those kind of bullet points which form the choices.

147
00:07:46,398 --> 00:07:48,781
So that's the kind of the linear film script

148
00:07:48,781 --> 00:07:51,223
on the right-hand side that's generated

149
00:07:51,223 --> 00:07:55,187
and that drives the machinery of what happens in the game.

150
00:07:56,203 --> 00:07:59,705
And we have a custom and quite a simple, actually,

151
00:07:59,705 --> 00:08:02,627
interpreter for how to interpret that text behind the scenes

152
00:08:02,627 --> 00:08:08,090
and produce the visual game, which I'll show you right now.

153
00:08:08,090 --> 00:08:11,572
So this is from the same script.

154
00:08:11,572 --> 00:08:12,633
Here, you can see we've got the 3D environments.

155
00:08:12,633 --> 00:08:14,394
We've got the 2D characters and the simple dialogue bubbles.

156
00:08:14,394 --> 00:08:15,515
You can see what it looks like when you make choices.

157
00:08:28,327 --> 00:08:32,072
And by the way, this isn't even a real environment from the game.

158
00:08:32,072 --> 00:08:35,336
This is from a Unity sample environment

159
00:08:35,336 --> 00:08:36,718
that I've hacked up just to put the characters in.

160
00:08:36,718 --> 00:08:41,204
And as you can see, it's pretty simple stuff so far.

161
00:08:44,968 --> 00:08:47,610
So this is just a literal piece of text

162
00:08:47,610 --> 00:08:50,852
that gets passed straight through from the ink

163
00:08:50,852 --> 00:08:51,893
directly into the game.

164
00:08:51,893 --> 00:08:54,955
And it's a really simple syntax, as you can see.

165
00:08:54,955 --> 00:08:57,056
We can just look for the position of the colon

166
00:08:57,056 --> 00:09:00,098
and separate it into which character is speaking

167
00:09:00,098 --> 00:09:01,038
and what do they say.

168
00:09:02,647 --> 00:09:04,548
Another cute thing that we do, and something

169
00:09:04,548 --> 00:09:06,109
that we've added to Ink in the last year,

170
00:09:06,109 --> 00:09:10,111
is the ability to add hashtags to individual lines.

171
00:09:10,111 --> 00:09:13,612
And what we're using this for here

172
00:09:13,612 --> 00:09:15,953
is the ability to just put a little smiley on the end,

173
00:09:15,953 --> 00:09:19,595
or an emoticon, and that will change the particular piece

174
00:09:19,595 --> 00:09:21,996
of art that we show.

175
00:09:21,996 --> 00:09:24,397
So we can put a little smiley on, on the end of the line,

176
00:09:24,397 --> 00:09:27,018
and the character will smile.

177
00:09:27,018 --> 00:09:28,079
So we've got a whole range of emoticons

178
00:09:28,079 --> 00:09:28,679
that we can use for that.

179
00:09:31,202 --> 00:09:32,843
Something else we can do that's really,

180
00:09:32,843 --> 00:09:34,324
a really very natural way to write,

181
00:09:34,324 --> 00:09:36,705
but again, it's just part of the game-specific syntax.

182
00:09:36,705 --> 00:09:40,167
So we can put these parenthesized

183
00:09:40,167 --> 00:09:42,008
little additional pieces of metadata

184
00:09:42,008 --> 00:09:44,290
to just say, right, this character

185
00:09:44,290 --> 00:09:45,591
is speaking to that character.

186
00:09:46,191 --> 00:09:50,854
And in the case of our protagonist, when she speaks,

187
00:09:50,854 --> 00:09:53,155
most of the time she actually doesn't talk directly

188
00:09:53,155 --> 00:09:56,917
to the sidekick robot because actually she's a bit aloof

189
00:09:56,917 --> 00:10:00,599
and she's actually more interested in the environment.

190
00:10:00,599 --> 00:10:02,520
So she kind of looks out into the world,

191
00:10:02,520 --> 00:10:04,521
she talks to Six and he's there,

192
00:10:04,521 --> 00:10:06,403
he looks at her by default.

193
00:10:06,403 --> 00:10:09,985
But if we really want her to go and turn and look at him,

194
00:10:09,985 --> 00:10:10,925
then we can do that as well.

195
00:10:13,050 --> 00:10:17,552
And then we could also change the pose.

196
00:10:17,552 --> 00:10:20,813
So when you put that in parentheses,

197
00:10:20,813 --> 00:10:22,954
it will just choose a particular piece of art

198
00:10:22,954 --> 00:10:27,416
that our artist has drawn for that particular moment.

199
00:10:27,416 --> 00:10:30,618
And it's just really easy and natural to write this stuff.

200
00:10:32,442 --> 00:10:36,024
And here's a genuine piece of ink syntax, finally.

201
00:10:36,024 --> 00:10:39,386
When you put an asterisk on the front, just adding that

202
00:10:39,386 --> 00:10:42,488
one thing will turn that line of dialogue into a choice.

203
00:10:42,488 --> 00:10:46,351
So we'll have a number of choices that look like that.

204
00:10:46,351 --> 00:10:48,712
And when you pick that line, that's what

205
00:10:48,712 --> 00:10:50,153
the character will say.

206
00:10:50,153 --> 00:10:55,396
But what happens if you have a choice with a character name

207
00:10:55,396 --> 00:10:57,798
that isn't your character, that isn't the protagonist?

208
00:10:58,416 --> 00:11:02,959
well, they also get the opportunity to say a line.

209
00:11:02,959 --> 00:11:07,542
And so whereas previously we were always

210
00:11:07,542 --> 00:11:11,285
using choices in the ink to allow the player to make

211
00:11:11,285 --> 00:11:14,247
choices in the game, we can also provide choices

212
00:11:14,247 --> 00:11:16,749
to allow other characters to contribute.

213
00:11:16,749 --> 00:11:18,450
And so what we use this for is a kind of,

214
00:11:18,450 --> 00:11:21,172
you've probably seen this in other games before,

215
00:11:21,172 --> 00:11:24,334
when you have a timeout, when if you don't say anything,

216
00:11:24,334 --> 00:11:26,996
then another character might interject with something.

217
00:11:27,947 --> 00:11:33,392
So it's really simple to add these extra little details.

218
00:11:33,392 --> 00:11:35,074
So all this dialogue is fine,

219
00:11:35,074 --> 00:11:37,476
but what we'd really like our protagonist to be able to do

220
00:11:37,476 --> 00:11:38,457
is explore a scene now.

221
00:11:38,457 --> 00:11:41,520
And that's not an obvious thing that you can do

222
00:11:41,520 --> 00:11:43,882
in a text adventure, or at least not in a way

223
00:11:43,882 --> 00:11:48,166
that would synchronize with a 3D explorable space.

224
00:11:50,037 --> 00:11:53,098
So this can be modeled in ink as well, and what we do is

225
00:11:53,098 --> 00:11:56,860
we take this idea of choices that aren't directly associated

226
00:11:56,860 --> 00:11:59,922
with visible concrete choices that the player makes,

227
00:11:59,922 --> 00:12:02,043
and we use that.

228
00:12:02,043 --> 00:12:04,044
So if you have a location that you want to walk to

229
00:12:04,044 --> 00:12:06,966
on the ground, you can choose to walk in exactly

230
00:12:06,966 --> 00:12:09,087
the same way that you would in any other game,

231
00:12:09,087 --> 00:12:11,729
whether it's through direct control on the left stick

232
00:12:11,729 --> 00:12:14,070
or by clicking on a marker within the world.

233
00:12:14,930 --> 00:12:17,652
And what the game will do behind the scenes is it will say,

234
00:12:17,652 --> 00:12:18,913
well, you made the choice to move.

235
00:12:18,913 --> 00:12:22,296
Therefore, we will pick that move choice.

236
00:12:22,296 --> 00:12:27,620
And so the dash in the middle is a piece of ink syntax,

237
00:12:27,620 --> 00:12:30,722
which is a way to control the flow.

238
00:12:30,722 --> 00:12:32,764
So once you've made a choice, then

239
00:12:32,764 --> 00:12:34,165
after you've made the choice, then it will.

240
00:12:34,545 --> 00:12:36,407
it'll choose that as the point to go to,

241
00:12:36,407 --> 00:12:38,568
to join the flow together.

242
00:12:38,568 --> 00:12:40,589
So what's happening here is you could actually

243
00:12:40,589 --> 00:12:43,051
put a piece of content in between

244
00:12:43,051 --> 00:12:44,471
moving and arriving.

245
00:12:44,471 --> 00:12:47,393
So the arrive choice is another choice,

246
00:12:47,393 --> 00:12:49,094
but it's even less directly

247
00:12:49,094 --> 00:12:50,135
related to

248
00:12:50,135 --> 00:12:53,077
the player making a specific decision,

249
00:12:53,077 --> 00:12:54,658
and it's just something that

250
00:12:54,658 --> 00:12:56,519
the game engine will tell

251
00:12:56,519 --> 00:12:58,620
the ink engine to do

252
00:12:58,620 --> 00:13:00,361
when you actually arrive at your

253
00:13:00,361 --> 00:13:01,362
target destination.

254
00:13:02,102 --> 00:13:06,784
But in between, you might choose to say something or just

255
00:13:06,784 --> 00:13:09,424
speak some lines of dialogue, or do anything else which is

